-- #561 (PR-A native + PR-B wasm, both SHIPPED) — strictness-parity regression
-- coverage for a value cycle whose back edge is HIDDEN behind interface-method
-- dispatch, the cyclic sibling to eager_global_dispatch_hidden.mdk (which pins
-- an ORDERING bug, not a cycle: `cell = mkVal True` there reaches a SAFE global
-- through a CMethod head that a topo sort's direct free-var scan can't follow).
--
-- Here the CMethod-hidden edge closes a real cycle: `cell = mk True` and
-- `mk _ = cell + 1` — the impl body reads `cell` right back. The topo sort
-- can't see the `cell -> cell` edge (it doesn't follow through a CMethod head,
-- same reason the ordering bug exists), but the LAZY-INIT machinery does not
-- need to see it structurally: it force-initializes `cell`, the force re-enters
-- `mk True` which reads `cell` while it is still being forced, and the
-- still-FORCING state raises E-CYCLIC-VALUE — exactly like a directly-visible
-- self cycle, just reached one dispatch hop later.
--
-- This fixture lives in the TYPED corpus deliberately, same reasoning as
-- eager_global_dispatch_hidden.mdk: the untyped llvm_fixtures/ probe is
-- prelude-free and typecheck-free, so it never produces the CMethod node that
-- makes this edge (and this bug class) exist at all.
--
-- The golden is EMPTY (this harness diffs STDOUT; the error goes to stderr).
--
-- Measured on the shipping engines (2026-07-18), all three post-#561:
--   eval   -> runtime error [E-CYCLIC-VALUE], exit 1, empty stdout
--   native -> runtime error [E-CYCLIC-VALUE], exit 1, empty stdout
--   wasm   -> runtime error [E-CYCLIC-VALUE], exit 1, empty stdout
--
-- If a future change makes dispatch-hidden cycle detection diverge from the
-- direct self-cycle case (e.g. a force-guard that only fires on a directly
-- visible self-reference), this fixture stops raising E-CYCLIC-VALUE on
-- whichever engine regressed, and the gate goes red. Do NOT delete it.

interface Mk a where
  mk : a -> Int

impl Mk Bool where
  mk _ = cell + 1

cell = mk True

main = cell
